{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"200bcb3e-1674-4206-a4e5-cb0f7aed3675","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe report confirms the overhead is **MSBuild process startup + project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild nodes warm in-process. The project itself is fine — the bottleneck is the CLI cold-start path.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the process alive and uses file watchers — no repeated startup cost:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server\nKeeps an MSBuild server process running between CLI invocations, eliminating cold-start overhead. Set the environment variable:\n```\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nOr add to `Directory.Build.props` so the whole team gets it:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <MSBuildServer>true</MSBuildServer>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### 3. Use graph-based builds\nThe `-graph` flag lets MSBuild evaluate the project graph up front and skip redundant work:\n```\ndotnet build -graph\n```\n\n### 4. Confirm node reuse is not disabled\nMSBuild reuses worker nodes by default, but some environments disable it. Verify `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` is **not** set to `1`, and you're not passing `-nodeReuse:false`.\n\n---\n\n**Biggest win**: For quick edit-build-test cycles, `dotnet watch build` is the closest CLI equivalent to the VS experience. Pairing it with `MSBuildServer=true` ensures even standalone `dotnet build` calls are fast when you do use them directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e5e0f80b-292a-490a-8ab4-65f2cd6c466c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds) even when nothing has changed, while Visual Studio builds nearly instantly. They've already ruled out analyzers and confirmed incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight here is the difference between how Visual Studio and `dotnet build` CLI work:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** keeps an MSBuild server/node running in the background, so project evaluation and compilation are done in a warm process.\n2. **`dotnet build` CLI** by default starts a new MSBuild process each time, paying startup and project evaluation costs on every invocation.\n\n\nThe solution is to enable the MSBuild Server in .NET 8+, which keeps MSBuild nodes alive between builds just like Visual Studio does—either by using the `--use-server` flag, setting `MSBuildServer=1`, or configuring the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable.\n\nFor iterative development, `dotnet watch build` is also valuable since it maintains a running process and uses file watchers to trigger incremental rebuilds, avoiding the repeated startup cost entirely.\n\nNode reuse with `/nodeReuse:true` (already the default for the CLI) keeps MSBuild worker processes alive between builds, though I should verify it hasn't been disabled somewhere.\n\nThe graph-based build with the `-graph` flag can also help optimize the evaluation phase. I'm wondering if there's something in a `Directory.Build.props` file that might be affecting performance, or if adding `<AccelerateBuildsInVisualStudio>` to the project file would make a meaningful difference.\n\nActually, that setting is Visual Studio-specific, so it won't help here. Looking back at the performance report, the real bottleneck is MSBuild process startup and the repeated re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation. The most practical fixes are using `dotnet watch build` to eliminate process startup during development, enabling the MSBuild server to keep things warm between invocations, and leveraging graph-based builds with the `-graph` flag. I should put together some concrete recommendations and maybe create a `Directory.Build.props` file with useful optimizations.","outputTokens":1245,"requestId":"141C:1E21:C8DFD9A:E03ADFE:69EC0DF3"},"id":"35692ad1-c115-4a11-b119-97d9ea7e751f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:42:54.711Z","parentId":"dcf5ff28-db6d-4337-bc60-8c8b7025d528"}
